## TO DISABLE ONLY PHANTOM TOUCHES

**Step 1.** Open the terminal (`Ctrl` + `Alt` + `T`) and run:

    sudo nano /etc/udev/rules.d/99-disable-touchscreen.rules


**Step 2.** Paste the following line exactly as it is below (already using the Vendor ID `04f3` and Product ID `2012` you identified):

    SUBSYSTEM=="input", ATTRS{idVendor}=="04f3", ATTRS{idProduct}=="2012", ENV{ID_INPUT}="", ENV{ID_INPUT_TOUCHSCREEN}="", ENV{ID_INPUT_MOUSE}="", ENV{ID_INPUT_TABLET}="", ENV{LIBINPUT_IGNORE_DEVICE}="1"

Save the file by pressing `Ctrl` + `O`, then `Enter`. Exit by pressing `Ctrl` + `X`.
  

**Step 3.** To apply the rule immediately without breaking anything, run:

    sudo udevadm control --reload-rules && sudo udevadm trigger



> [!NOTE]
> If the screen doesn't stop responding immediately, simply restart your laptop one last time.




## DISABLING THE TOUCHSCREEN COMPLETELY

**Step 1.** Open the terminal (`Ctrl` + `Alt` + `T`) and open our rules file for editing:

      
    sudo nano /etc/udev/rules.d/99-disable-touchscreen.rules



**Step 2.** Delete everything inside and replace it with this new command line (it intercepts the moment the driver tries to connect to the screen and forces it to unbind):


    ACTION=="bind", SUBSYSTEM=="hid", ATTRS{idVendor}=="04f3", ATTRS{idProduct}=="2012", RUN+="/bin/sh -c 'echo -n %k > /sys/bus/hid/devices/%k/driver/unbind'"


Save the file by pressing `Ctrl` + `O`, then `Enter`. Exit with `Ctrl` + `X`.
  

  
**Step 3.** Restart the computer so Linux applies the block from boot:


    sudo reboot
